text = "Mucus: Slimy goo that slows down pathogens by trapping them. 
Macrophage: iA white blood cell that engulfs pathogens. They digest pathogens they engulf and present the antigen fragment on their MHC II complex for helper T cells to bind. B 
Neutrophil kills pathogens using toxins and ingest them. 
Dendritic cells ingest pathogens (as well as dead ones) and present them on MHC to activate other immune cells. 
B cells recognize antigens, secrete antibodies, and proliferate. There are two types of B cells: plasma cells and memory cells. Plasma cells secrete antibodies in order to mark pathogens for destruction. Memory cells are able to recognize foreign antigens faster in future infections. 
Cytotoxic T cells produce cytotoxins, which trigger infected cells to undergo apoptosis. They can bind to antigen presented on MHC I, where it can be triggered by cytokines produced by a helper T cell that is bound to antigen on MHC II. Then, these active cytotoxic T cells proliferate, killing infected cells. 
Helper T cells recognize antigens presented on MHC and secrete cytokines, which activate immune cells such as B cells, cytotoxic T cells, and macrophages. "
